errataReason: This errata version of the assessment was created to attach the  corrected distribution map. The previous amended version of the 2015  assessment (which added two countries to the countries of occurrence  (Azerbaijan and Russian Federation), provided more details in the  'Geographic Range' section, and added an Assessor that was missing from  the previously published assessment) accidentally used the older version  of the map.

assessor: Glatston, A., Wei, F., Than Zaw & Sherpa, A.
errataReason: Corrected the spelling of an authors name used as a reference from Kendal, K., to Kandel, K., in the reference "Kendal, K., Huettmann, F., Krishna Suwal, M., Regmi, G.R., Nijman, V., Nekaris, K.A.I., Sonam Tashi Lama, Thapa, A., Sharma, H.P. and Subedi, T.R. 2015. Biological Conservation 181: 150–161".

assessor: Ojeda, R., Bidau, C. & Emmons, L.
errataReason: This errata assessment has been created because the map was accidentally left out of the version published previously. In addition to these previous errata changes, a number of European countries have been added to the Countries of Occurrence table, that had previously been mentioned in the text.

assessor: Swaisgood, R., Wang, D. & Wei, F.
errataReason: Typo in the conservation actions section that read The Giant Panda has been the focus of none of the most intensive changed none to one.In addition to this change, a further type in the rational section which read they plant to continue investing has been changed to read they plan to continue investing.

reviewer: Reeves, R., Taylor, B.L. & Braulik, G.
errataReason:
This errata version of the 2018 assessment was created to correct parts of the text in the Threats section:
  • Rates of hooking or entanglement are approximately 1.5 individuals for every 10 million hooks set is now corrected to Rates of hooking or entanglement are approximately 1.5 individuals for every 1 million hooks set.
  • Observers on Spanish longline vessels documented two bycaught False Killer Whales off the Azores in 2006 in approximately 810,000 observed hooks (Hernandez-Milian et al. 2008), a rate more than 15 times higher than in the Hawaii-based longline fishery is now corrected to Observers on Spanish longline vessels documented two bycaught False Killer Whales off the Azores in 2006 in approximately 810,000 observed hooks (Hernandez-Milian et al. 2008), a rate similar to the Hawaii-based longline fishery..

assessor: de Jong, Y.A., Cumming, D., d'Huart, J. & Butynski, T.
errataReason: Corrected the title used in the reference Butynski, T.M. and De Jong, Y.A. In prep. Common Warthog (Phacochoerus africanus). In: M. Melletti and E. Meijaard (eds), Ecology, Evolution and Management of Wild Pigs and Peccaries. Implications for Conservation. So that it now correctly reads: Butynski, T.M. and De Jong, Y.A. In prep. Common Warthog (Phacochoerus africanus). In: M. Melletti and E. Meijaard (eds), Ecology, Conservation and Management of Wild Pigs and Peccaries. Cambridge University Press.

The original version of the 2015 assessment stated in the Habitats and Ecology section that "Monk Seals are known to eat more than 530 prey species"; this should have read "Monk Seals are known to eat more than 70 prey species". This errata version of the assessment corrects this statement.

assessor: Do Linh San, E., Gaubert, P., Wondmagegne, D. & Ray, J.
amendedReason: Occurrence of the species on Sao Tome Island was reported in the Geographic Range text originally, but it was not stated that this was as a result of an introduction and Sao Tome was not coded under the Countries of Occurrence. This amended version corrects these errors. The range map has not been updated to reflect the introduced range.

assessor: Stein, A.B., Athreya, V., Gerngross, P., Balme, G., Henschel, P., Karanth, U., Miquelle, D., Rostro-Garcia, S., Kamler, J.F., Laguardia, A., Khorozyan, I. & Ghoddousi, A.
reviewer: Nowell, K., Hunter, L., Duckworth, J.W., Breitenmoser-Würsten, C., Lanz, T. & Breitenmoser, U.
amendedReason: This is a slightly updated version of the amended version of the 2015 assessment, which was created for the 2019-3 Red List to update the distribution map for this species. The map was updated based on more recent data available from the Red List assessment for P. p. delacouri (Rostro-García et al. 2019, not Rostro-García et al. 2016 as previously noted). The reference for the more recent subspecies assessment has also been attached.

assessor: McDonald, R.A., Abramov, A.V., Stubbe, M., Herrero, J., Maran, T., Tikhonov, A., Cavallini, P., Kranz, A., Giannatos, G., Kry�tufek, B. & Reid, F.
amendedReason: Occurrence of the species on the Azores and Sao Tome Island were reported in the Geographic Range text originally but not coded under the Countries of Occurrence. This amended version corrects these errors. The range map has not been updated to reflect the introduced range.

assessor: McLellan, B.N., Proctor, M.F., Huber, D. & Michel, S.
amendedReason: The coding of the species' presence in Andorra, Austria, Czech Republic, and Turkmenistan was changed from "Certain" to "Uncertain" as bears are only occasionally present in these countries; likewise the presence in Switzerland was changed from "Reintroduced" to "Uncertain". Minor corrections have also been made to the text capitalizing the common names of species and correcting "population" to "subpopulation".

The spatial distribution and spatial data for this assessment are based on a paper published by Lewis, J.C., Powell, R.A. and Zielinski, W.J. 2012, but who were not cited in the paper as being the source of this data. A reference has now been included, and the spatial data for this assessment updated to reflect the correct source for this data.
